.SH FUNCTIONS
.LP
.B
\fBadd_handler(HandlerId, Module, Config) -> ok | {error, term()}\fR
\fB                     when\fR
\fB                         HandlerId :: logger_handler:id(),\fR
\fB                         Module :: module(),\fR
\fB                         Config :: logger_handler:config().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Add a handler with the given configuration.

.PP
\fIHandlerId\fR is a unique identifier which must be used in all subsequent calls referring to this handler.


.RE
.B
\fBadd_handler_filter(HandlerId, FilterId, Filter) ->\fR
\fB                            ok | {error, term()}\fR
\fB                            when\fR
\fB                                HandlerId :: logger_handler:id(),\fR
\fB                                FilterId :: filter_id(),\fR
\fB                                Filter :: filter().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Add a filter to the specified handler.

.PP
The filter fun is called with the log event as the first parameter, and the specified \fIfilter_args()\fR as the second parameter.

.PP
The return value of the fun specifies if a log event is to be discarded or forwarded to the handler callback:

log_event/0
.RS 2
The filter 
\fIpassed\fR. The next handler filter, if any, is applied. If no more filters exist for this handler, the log event is forwarded to the handler callback.

.RE

stop
.RS 2
The filter 
\fIdid not pass\fR, and the log event is immediately discarded.

.RE

ignore
.RS 2
The filter has no knowledge of the log event. The next handler filter, if any, is applied. If no more filters exist for this handler, the value of the 
\fIfilter_default\fR configuration parameter for the handler specifies if the log event shall be discarded or forwarded to the handler callback.

.RE

.PP
See section Filters in the User's Guide for more information about filters.

.PP
Some built-in filters exist. These are defined in \fIlogger_filters\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBadd_handlers(Application) -> ok | {error, term()}\fR
\fB                      when Application :: atom();\fR
\fB                  (HandlerConfig) -> ok | {error, term()}\fR
\fB                      when HandlerConfig :: [config_handler()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Reads the application configuration parameter \fIlogger\fR and calls \fIadd_handlers/1\fR with its contents.

.PP
This function should be used by custom Logger handlers to make configuration consistent no matter which handler the system uses. Normal usage is to add a call to \fIlogger:add_handlers/1\fR just after the processes that the handler needs are started, and pass the application's \fIlogger\fR configuration as the argument. For example:

.IP
.nf
-behaviour(application).
start(_, []) ->
    case supervisor:start_link({local, my_sup}, my_sup, []) of
        {ok, Pid} ->
            ok = logger:add_handlers(my_app),
            {ok, Pid, []};
        Error -> Error
     end.

.fi

.PP
This reads the \fIlogger\fR configuration parameter from the \fImy_app\fR application and starts the configured handlers. The contents of the configuration use the same rules as the logger handler configuration.

.PP
If the handler is meant to replace the default handler, the Kernel's default handler have to be disabled before the new handler is added. A \fIsys.config\fR file that disables the Kernel handler and adds a custom handler could look like this:

.IP
.nf
[{kernel,
  [{logger,
    %% Disable the default Kernel handler
    [{handler, default, undefined}]}]},
 {my_app,
  [{logger,
    %% Enable this handler as the default
    [{handler, default, my_handler, #{}}]}]}].

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBadd_primary_filter(FilterId, Filter) -> ok | {error, term()}\fR
\fB                            when\fR
\fB                                FilterId :: filter_id(),\fR
\fB                                Filter :: filter().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Add a primary filter to Logger.

.PP
The filter fun is called with the log event as the first parameter, and the specified \fIfilter_args()\fR as the second parameter.

.PP
The return value of the fun specifies if a log event is to be discarded or forwarded to the handlers:

log_event/0
.RS 2
The filter 
\fIpassed\fR. The next primary filter, if any, is applied. If no more primary filters exist, the log event is forwarded to the handler part of Logger, where handler filters are applied.

.RE

stop
.RS 2
The filter 
\fIdid not pass\fR, and the log event is immediately discarded.

.RE

ignore
.RS 2
The filter has no knowledge of the log event. The next primary filter, if any, is applied. If no more primary filters exist, the value of the primary 
\fIfilter_default\fR configuration parameter specifies if the log event shall be discarded or forwarded to the handler part.

.RE

.PP
See section Filters in the User's Guide for more information about filters.

.PP
Some built-in filters exist. These are defined in \fIlogger_filters\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBalert(String :: unicode:chardata(), Metadata :: metadata()) -> ok;\fR
\fB           (Report :: report(), Metadata :: metadata()) -> ok;\fR
\fB           (Format :: io:format(), Args :: [term()]) -> ok;\fR
\fB           (Fun :: msg_fun(), FunArgs :: term()) -> ok.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
